    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Should McVeigh Receive the Death Penalty?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Maurice Jay Baumgarten letter on June 4 editorial opposing death penalty for Timothy J McVeigh (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your June 4 editorial opposing the death penalty for Timothy J. McVeigh is self-contradictory. On one hand you suggest that the death penalty is inappropriate because of lingering questions about the case like ''the inability of the prosecution to place the defendant at the crime scene.'' Yet you go on to suggest that the jury should return a verdict of life without parole because ''that would be the most excruciating punishment of all'' for Mr. McVeigh.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your June 4 editorial opposing the death penalty for Timothy J. McVeigh is self-contradictory. On one hand you suggest that the death penalty is inappropriate because of lingering questions about the case like ''the inability of the prosecution to place the defendant at the crime scene.'' Yet you go on to suggest that the jury should return a verdict of life without parole because ''that would be the most excruciating punishment of all'' for Mr. McVeigh.</p>
        <p>Well, which is it? If there are any reasonable doubts about Mr. McVeigh's guilt, why should he be punished at all, let alone receive ''the most excruciating punishment of all''? If there are no doubts, why shouldn't he receive the death penalty?</p>
        <p>MAURICE JAY BAUMGARTEN</p>
        <p>Miami Beach, June 4, 1997</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
